column168: A JACK B KELLY, LEASED TRACTOR TRANSPORTING A LIQUID HELIUM TRAILER BELONGING TO PRAXAIR, OVERTURNED AT MM 131 ON I-80 NEAR DES MOINES, IOWA. THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 05:45 ON 03/1/1997.  THE DRIVER WAS ENCOUNTERING HEAVY FOG.  HE DROPPED THE TIRES, ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE UNIT, OFF OF THE PAVED ROADWAY.  THE TRACTOR HIT A GUARDRAIL, THE TRAILER HIT A CONCRETE DRAINAGE WALL AND BECAME DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRACTOR. THE TRACTOR OVERTURNED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY AND THE TRAILER CAME TO REST IN AN OPEN FIELD ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED ONLY A RESIDUAL AMOUNT OF HELIUM.  THE TRAILER IS VACUUM JACKETED.  TNE N2 DEVERTER HOUSING ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND CAUSED A LOSS OF VACUUM ON THE VESSEL.  WHEN THE  VACUUM WAS LOST, THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT INSIDE THE INNER VESSEL STARTED TO WARM UP.  LIQUID HELIUM IS -452.7 DEGREES F.  THE LOSS OF VACUUM AND THE WARMING OF THE PRODUCT CAUSE THE PRESSURE TO RISE IN THE INNER VESSEL.  THE INNER VESSEL WAS NOT RUPTURED. BEFORE THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE ACTIVATED, THE DRIVER OPENED THE MANUAL VENTING SYSTEM AND VENTED THE REMAINING RESIDUAL HELIUM TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE VENTING BY THE DRIVER WAS A CONTROLLED RELEASE.  AFTER THE TRAILER REACHED ZERO PRESSURE, IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE HIGHWAY RIGHT OF WAY. THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE GUARDRAIL, ESTIMATED AT $3500.00.  NO FLUIDS WERE LOST FROM THE TRACTOR (IE: FUEL, OIL, ANTIFREEZE).  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, THE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER VIA CELLULAR TELEPHONE. THE DRIVERS WERE NOT INJURED.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING A SEATBELT.  THE POLICE ARRIVED JUST MINUTES AFTER THE ACCIDENT.  THE FOLLOWING WEEK WE HELD A SAFETY MEETING AT THE HOME TERMINAL OF THE DRIVER.  THIS ACCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED IN DETAIL.  WE ALSO VIDEO TAPED A PRESENTATION OF THE ACCIDENT SO THAT ALL DRIVERS WILL BE INFORMED.  THE OWNER OPERATOR WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO DELIVER PRODUCTS DISPATCHED BY JACK B KELLEY INC.

THE DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO HAUL A LOAD OF #2 DIESEL FUEL TO NEAL SIMPSON #2.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE DESTINATION, HE STARTED UNLOADING AT NEIL SIMPSON #1.  HE FAILED TO LOOK AT HIS FREIGHT BILL AND ORDERS.  THE TANK AT NEIL SIMPSON #1 WAS ALMOST FULL WHEN HE STARTED UNLOADING, BUT THERE WAS NO WAY FOR THE DRIVER TO GAUGE THE TANK.  WHEN THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE VENT PIPE HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN VALVES.  ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS 25 TO 50 GALLONS.  THE SPILL WAS IN A CONTAINMENT AREA.  THERE WAS QUITE A BIT OF WATER IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA FROM MELTING SNOW.  THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS PUMPED OUT AND THE WATER DIESEL MIX WAS DISPOSED OF.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN DRIVERS ARE TO CHECK IN AT THE POWER PLANT OFFICE AND MAKE SURE THEY GO TO THE RIGHT TANK.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:35 A.M. ON THE MORNING OF MARCH 6, 1997, N&M TRANSFER EXPERIENCED A 300 GALLON CHEMICAL SPILL THAT RESULTED FROM A CRACKED VALVE ON A DOT EXEMPTION TANK (DOT E-9150). THIS TANK WAS ORIGINALLY PICKED UP BY N&M TRANSFER FROM THE SHIPPER (CHASKA CHEMICAL, SAVAGE, MN). THE TANK WAS LOADED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF CHASKA CHEMICAL AT THE TIME OF PICK UP. IT WAS HAULED TO N&M TRANSFER, NEEMAH, WI, IN THE SAME TRAILER. ** OUR RECORDS INDICATE THAT THE TANK ARRIVED SAFELY AND INTACT AND THAT IT WAS SAFELY PLACED ON OUR DOCK FOR ONLY 1-3 HOURS BEFORE ANOTHER DOCKMAN ATTEMPTED TO PICK IT UP FOR LOADING. OUR INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT AFTER PROPERLY INSERTING THE FORKS IN THE SLOTTED FORK GROOVES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, OUR DOCKMAN BEGAN LIFTING THE TANK OFF OF THE CONCRETE DOCK FLOOR. JUST MOMENTS AFTER PICKING UP THE TANK THE VALVE CRACKED AND THE CONTENTS BEGAN POURING OUT. STATEMENTS BY EMPLOYEES IN THE AREA NOTED THAT AT NO TIME WAS THE VALVE HIT BY THE DOCKMAN. SHORTLY AFTER THE LEAKAGE BEGAN ANOTHER DOCKMAN ATTEMPED TO TILT THE TANK TO MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE. THE TILTING OF THE TANK CAUSED A RUPTURE IN THE BACK MID POINT OF THE TANK, WHICH RESULTED IN THE COMPLETE SPILLAGE OF TANK CONTENTS WITHIN MINUTES AFTER THE INITIAL VALVE CRACKING. ** EMERGENCY PERSONNEL FROM THE TOWN OF NEENAH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE WINNEBAGO COUNTY HAZ/MAT TEAM WERE NOTIFIED AND ON THE SCENE WITHIN THE HOUR. THE WISCONSIN DNR WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. A PRIVATE REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO COMPLETE BY 2:30 P.M. ** THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO AN AREA OF ABOUT 50' BY 40' N&M TRANSFER EMPLOYEES USED GRANDULATED DRI-ZORB, PADS, PILLOWS, AND DIAPERS (CARGO) TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE DOCK SUPERVISOR ON DUTY IMMEDIATELY ORDERED YARDMEN TO BEGIN PULLING TRAILERS OUT OF THE DOCK SO THAT PROPER VENTILATION COULD BE ATTAINED. (THIS BUILDING IS A CROSS DOCK OPERATION). ALL EMPLOYEES (OTHER THAN FOREMAN AND SUPERVISORS) WERE EVACUATED FROM THE BUILDING WITHIN 15 MINUTES OFTHE SPILL. NINE DOCK EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION ONLY. ANOTHER NINE DOCK EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED IN THEIR OWN PERSONAL VEHICLES FOR OBSERVATION ONLY. ** ON TUESDAY MARCH 18TH, N&M TRANSFER REQUESTED A MEETING WITH THE TOWN OF NEENAH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE INCIDENT COMMANDER FROM THE WINNEBAGO COUNTY HAZ/MAT TEAM. DURING THIS MEETING WE EVALUATED HOW THE SPILL WAS HANDLED BY THESE AGENCIES AND BY N&M TRANSFER EMPLOYEES. AS A RESULT OF THIS MEETING, N&M TRANSFER IS CURRENTLY LOOKING AT THE FEASIBILITY AND COSTS OF USING A CONTAINMENT TYPE SYSTEM CAPABLE OF HOLDING BULK QUANTITIES OF SPILLED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WE ARE ALSO REVIEWING THE COSTS AND RISKS INVOLVED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (E.G. CORROSIVES, FLAMMABLE, POISONS). DURING OUR ANNUAL SUPERVISORY HAZ/MAT RE-TRAINING WE WILL ALSO DISCUSS THIS SPILL IN DETAIL. ** I HAVE INCLUDED PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE CONTAINER (TANK) IN QUESTION, ALONG WITH PHOTOS OF THE SPILL SCENE AND CLEAN UP OPERATIONS. I AM ALS

THE TRUCK DRIVER MOVED THE DRUM IMMEDIATELY.  THE INJURED PERSON WAS TREATED FOR CHEMICAL BURNS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PLACED IN A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DEFECTIVE DRUM WAS RETURNED & REMOVED FROM SERVICE.
DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER AND BEHIND SKID WAS THE DRUM, AND WHEN HE WENT TO PICK IT UP HE PUNCTURED THE DRUM.
AS DOCKMAN WAS LOADING A PALLET OF THIS MATERIAL ONTO TRAILER, A CARTON ON THE BOTTOM OF PALLET STRUCK A STEEL PIPE THAT WAS PROTRUDING FROM OTHER FREIGHT ALREADY IN THE TRAILER.

DRIVER WAS FILLING UNDERGROUND HEATING FUEL TANK.  WHEN HE FINISHED AND PULLED OUT THE FILL HOSE, THE FUEL BLEW BACK OUT OF THE FILL PIPE SPRAYING THE AREA AROUND THE FILL AREA WITH DIESEL.  WIND WAS BLOWING HARD AT THE TIME AND SPREAD DIESEL SPRAY IN A LARGE AREA.  FUEL WAS SPRAYED ON GRAVEL DRIVEWAY AND SIDE OF BRICK HOUSE.  THE SOIL IS REMOVED AND NEW SOIL AND GRAVEL REPLACED.  SIDE OF HOUSE WASHED DOWN.

THE BULK INTERMODAL DISTRIBUTOR FACILITY (BIDS) AT CHATTANOOGA, TN WAS TAKING A LOAD OFF GATX61333 WHEN THE RUPTURE DISK BLEW, RELEASING AN UNKNOWN QUANTITY OF ACID VAPORS.  THE CAR WAS BEING TRANSLOADED WITH 10 PSIG OF PRESSURE ON THE CAR.  THE TRANSLOADING PROCESS WAS STOPPED, THE CAR WAS DEPRESSURIZED AND BIDS PERSONNEL REPLACED THE BLOWN DISK.

TRAIN MASTER REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN HOLLAND, MI.  CAR HAS A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  TRAIN MASTER CALLED A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND CORRECT PROBLEM.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT ALL THE SECUREMENT BOLTS ON THE LIQUID VALVE WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  THEY MADE THE BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

MECHANICAL FORCES AT CSXT'S RAILYARD IN ERWIN, TN WERE PREPARING TO DO SOME HOT WORK ON A TGOX30657.  THEY USED A VOLATILE ORGANIC VAPOR "SNIFFER" TO CHECK FOR LEAKS AND GOT AN INDICATION VAPORS WERE PRESENT. CSXT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR FOR LEAKS.  CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON TOP OF THE CAR BUT 1 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLT WAS LOOSE.  THEY FOUND SOME PRODUCT SEEPING AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  THE MANWAY BOLT AND THE BOTTOM CAP WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CONTRACTOR STOOD BY WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS METER WHILE THE HOT WORK WAS DONE.

AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN SUMTER, SC, A SWITCH CREW OBSERVED TLDX216003 TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER SENT A RESCAR MOBILE REPAIR UNIT TO REPAIR THE CAR.  RESCAR REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.

TRAIN Q60205 WAS PULLING OUT OF CSXT'S RAILYARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA WHEN GATX27758 WAS SPOTTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS CUT OUT AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE YARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR A CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND STOP THE LEAK. CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS SHELL FULL AND PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT AROUND THE MANWAY COVER.  THE SHIPPER SENT A TANKER TRUCK TO REMOVE SOME PRODUCT.  TRUCK ARRIVES EARLY HOURS ON 3/6 AND TOOK 2000 GALLONS OFF THE TANK CAR.  THE TRUCK TOOK THE PRODUCT BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY.

TANK CAR OBSERVED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT RAILYARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  CAR ISOLATED.  LA STATE POLICE AND N.O. FIRE DEPT. NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC.  A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND SOME OF THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT AND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS CRACKED AND BADLY WORN.  THE CONTRACTOR MADE A TEMPORARY GASKET WITH TEFLON ROPE.  RESCAR RESPONDED LATER THAT NIGHT AND REPLACED THE TEMPORARY GASKET WITH A PROPER GASKET.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED.

TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATIONS RAILYARD IN SAVANNAH, GA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT CALLED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SCENE EARLY ON 3/6 AND FOUND THE CAR WAS PRESSURIZED WITH THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE CAP NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE PRESSURE WAS BLED OFF AND THE CAP WAS MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE MANWAY GASKET AND THE RUPTURE DISK WERE INSPECTED AND OK'D.

DRIVER WAS FILLING ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK, LEFT HOSE IN TANK AND WALKED AWAY.  CUSTOMER PULLED HOSE OUT UNAWARE THE FUELING WAS IN PROCESS TO ADD A DIESEL ADDITIVE.  WHEN NOZZLE WAS PULLED OUT SOME PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF TANK ONTO CEMENT FLOOR.  IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF NOZZLE.   CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENTS THEN DRIVER CALLED OFFICE TO INFORM ME OF INCIDENT.  THEN COMPLETED DELIVERY.  RECOMMEND EMPLOYEE'S KEEP PEOPLE OUT OF AREA WHILE FUELING, BE MORE ATTENTIVE TO WHAT'S GOING ON AND COMMUNICATE WITH CUSTOMERS IF THEY PLAN TO DO SOMETHING BEFORE START OF DELIVERY.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE, DRIVER STOPPED TO CHECK HIS LOAD AND HE NOTICED SOME PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM PACKAGE.  THE TRAILER HAD SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THIS CAR WAS FOUND WITH PRODUCT ON THE CAR SIDES WHILE IN THE BOWL TRACKS. TWO ADDITIONAL AREAS WERE LOCATED WHERE SMALL POOLS OF THE PRODUCT WERE ADJACENT TO THE TRACK.  THE CAR WAS THEN TAKEN TO AN ISOLATION AREA.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  A 100# RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED.  BNSF'S ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE CAR AND GROUND.

DRUM WAS PUNCTURED ENROUTE TO DESTINATION(PERRYSBURGH OH).  LOAD SHIFT AND TOTE TANK PUNCTURED DRUM.  RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE PACKAGING MORE LOAD BARS SHOULD BE USED TO LOCK DOWN TOTE TANK.  KEPT ALL MATERIALS CONTAINED INSIDE TRUCK BY USING SPILL KIT.

THE DRIVER STAYED PARKED IN ONE SPOT FOR SEVERAL HOURS THEN MADE ENTRY INTO TRAILER WITH PROPER PPE ON.  HE NOTICED THE BUNG IN ONE DRUM WAS LOOSE AND PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED THE PACKAGE.  HE TIGHTENED THE BUNG AND APPLIED ABSORBING MATERIAL TO THE PRODUCT ON FLOOR OF TRL - MOST OF PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED BY THIS TIME.  UPON ARRIVAL AT FACILITY THE DRUMS WERE OFF LOADED AND THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED.
BAGS STACKED TWO HIGH ON THE PALLETS, FREIGHT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT CAUSING BAGS TO FALL.

column168: DRIVER WAS ON HIGHWAY AND WHEN HE CAME TO INTERSECTION HE JUDGED THAT EVASIVE STEERING ACTION WAS REQUIRED TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH AUTOMOBILE AT INTERSECTION.  TRACTOR TRAILER ROLLED OVER INTO DITCH.  DRIVER INJURED FROM TRUCK ROLLOVER, NOT FROM EXPOSURE TO PRODUCT.  THERE WAS A SLOW DRIP LEAK FROM THE TRAILER DOME.  CARRIER EMERGENCY RESPONSE TECHNICIAN WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE FROM BATON ROUGE (2 HOURS ETA) AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO CLEAN UP.  (OVAC CO- 318-436-5712).  UNTIL CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED AND LEAK CONTAINED, 10 TO 12 HOMES AND A RESTAURANT WERE EVACUATED.  NO KNOWN INJURIES DUE TO PRODUCT.

THIS CAME INTO ORLANDO FROM ATLANTA AND WE FOUND THAT 1 CTN HAD BEEN LEAKING SO WE HELD THE CTN AT OUR DOCK.  APPEARS THAT IT HAD BEEN RAMMED AND CAUSED SOME LEAKAGE.  FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE NECK OF THE BOTTLE. THE SHIPPER DID NOT WANT IT BACK SO IT WAS SECURED AND SENT TO SALVAGE.

WHILE LOADING CRUDE OIL AT LEASE SITE, THE TRAILER GAUGE STUCK AND DRIVER OVER-FILLED TRAILED. IN FUTURE, DRIVER WILL VISUALLY INSPECT TRAILER WHILE LOADING.
DRIVER OVER-FILLED UNLOADING STATION STORAGE TANK DUE TO FAULTY MECHANICAL GAUGE ON TANK.  DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO VISUALLY INSPECT TANK FOR AVAILABLE STORAGE ROOM PRIOR TO UNLOADING TRUCK.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE PORT WASHINGTON FACILITY, THE DRIVERS NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING OUT THE BACK OF THE DUMP TRAILERS.  THE TRAILERS WERE PULLED INTO AN AREA OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND THE WASTE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO LINED ROLLOFF BOXES.  THE DUMP TRAILERS HAD AN INCH OF ICE IN THE BOTTOM WHEN LOADED.  THE TRAILERS WERE PLACED IN A HEATED GARAGE OVER THE WEEKEND FOR MONDAY DELIVERY.  THE DRIVERS NOTED WATER UNDER THE TRAILERS WHEN PERFORMNG THEIR PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS, BUT DECIDED IT WAS WATER THAT HAD MELTED OFF THE TRAILERS.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  DRIVERS ARE TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT ALL SPILLS OR POTENTIAL SPILLS.  TRAILERS BEING USED WERE SIFTPROOF NON-DOT SPECIFICATION TRAILERS.  ALTHOUGH SIFTPROOF, THE TRAILERS ARE NOT LIQUID TIGHT CONTAINERS.  LABORATORY ANALYSIS OF THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL (ATTACHED) SHOW NO DETECT OF THE CHLORINATED SOLVENTS AND MERCURY LEVELS BELOW RCRA LIMITS.  IF THE WASTE WERE NOT A RCRA "LISTED" WASTE, THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT MATERIAL WOULD PROVE TO BE NONHAZARDOUS.

column168: (A - E) TRANSPORTATION ACCIDENT INVOLVING A TRACTOR TRAILER CARRYING BEVERAGE CONCENTRATE AND A VAN RESULTING IN TWO FATALITIES.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS MOVING DOWNHILL TOWARDS THE CITY OF CAGUAS WHEN THE VEHICLE WENT OUT OF CONTROL INVADING THE OPPOSITE LANES AND HITTING A VAN THAT WAS GOING UPHILL TOWARD CIDRA.  THE TRAILER OVERTURNED AND SPLIT OPEN, SPILLING THE CARGO TO THE LEFT DOWNHILL SIDE OF STATE ROAD 172.  THIS CAUSED SOME OF THE DRUMS, PAILS AND JUGS TO PUNCTURE, CRUSH, RUPTURE OR BECOME UNCAPPED. THE LEAKING CONTAINERS AND ALL THE SPILLED MATERIAL WERE REMOVED BY OCHOA, IND.  SALES CORP., ENV. SERVICE DIV. AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, 5303 128TH AVENUE NORTH, CLEARWATER, FLORIDA.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TAKEN BY THE PR POLICE DEPT. TO THEIR CAGUAS FAC. FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

column168: WN CONTRACT GROUND EQUIPMENT MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL AT BWI SHIPPED AN ENGINE IN THE FORWARD BIN OF THE AIRCRAFT TO MDW.  UPON ARRIVAL AT MDW, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SHIPPING CONTAINER EMITTED FUEL FUMES.  THE SHIPPING AGENT, WHO BELIEVED THAT THE MOTOR HAD BEEN PROPERLY PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT, HAS BEEN APPROPRIATELY DISCIPLINED AS A RESULT.

AFTER MAKING THEIR DELIVERY AT HERCULES IN BRUNSWICK, GA, THE DRIVERS WERE RETURNING IN AN EMPTY CONDITION TO THEIR TERMINAL IN PACE, FL.  BEFORE DEPARTING THE CUSTOMER, THE DRIVERS FAILED TO PROPERLY STABILIZE THE RESIDULE PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER WHICH RESULTED IN A PRESSURE RISE ENROUTE.  THE DRIVERS NOTICED THE PRESSURE RISE AND STOPPED IN A REMOTE AREA AT AN EXIT RAMP SERVICE ROAD AND MANUALLY VENTED THE PRESSURE AND STABILIZED THE TRAILER.  THEY CONTINUED ON TO THEIR HOME TERMINAL IN PACE, FL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE DRIVERS WILL RECEIVE REMEDIAL TRAINING REGARDING TRAILER PRESSURE STABILIZATION.

DRIVER STOPPED TO DO TIRE CHECK AND UPON INSPECTING THE LOAD HE NOTICED PRODUCT ON FLOOR OF TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY APPLIED FLOOR DRY TO PRODUCT AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED THEIR PEOPLE OUT TO OVERPACK LEAKING DRUM AND TO CLEAN TRAILER.

DRIVER ERROR.  DRIVER CONNECTED FUEL HOSES IN REVERSE, CAUSING FUEL TO BE PUMPED BACK INTO TANKER AND OUT THE TANK VENTS.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTAINED SPILL AND PERFORMED INITIAL CLEAN UP.  ALL WASTE TRANSPORTATION AND REMEDIATION PERFORMED CLEAN UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  THE CONTAINER HAD ONE 55 GALLON 1H1 Y1.8 150 95 DRUM THAT HAD A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND THE DRUM HAD BEEN SUCKED IN TO THE POINT THE OPPOSITE SIDES OF THE DRUM WERE TOUCHING. THIS DRUM WAS ONE OF FOUR BANDED AND SHRINK UNDER THE DRUM.  THE PUNCTURE WAS CAUSED DUE TO A SECUREMENT PALLET BOARD BREAKING.  THIS ALLOWED THE DRUM TO FALL AND ROTATE INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR REMOVED AND OVERPACKED THE CRUSHED DRUM AND CLEANED UP SPILL.  THE CONTAINER WAS RETURNED TO FREIBORNE INDUSTRIES, INC. column168: RAILROAD COMMISSION OF TEXAS HAZMAT INSPECTOR FOUND THIS TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  A ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION WAS BEING CONDUCTED AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY. UPON TIGHTENING THE PLUG, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  CAR WAS OK TO MOVE TO DESTINATION, BUT WILL BE SHOPPED WHEN UNLOADED.  THE SHIPPER HAS RECEIVED A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE RELEASING PRODUCT DURING A ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION BY  HAZMAT INSPECTOR FROM THE RAILROAD COMMISSION OF TEXAS. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND LEAKAGE AT BOTH THE LIQUID LINE AND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE LIQUID VALVE WAS RESEATED TO STOP THE LEAKAGE; HOWEVER, A REPLACEMENT SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REQUIRED.  A REPAIR CONTRACTOR HANDLED THIS REPAIR PRIOR TO RELEASING THE CAR TO DESTINATION.

column168: THIS CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHEN DERAMPING AT THE DESTINATION RAIL TERMINAL.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED LOAD AND NOTED INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING AND BRACING TO RESTRAIN THE VARIOUS PACKAGINGS.  THE SHIPPERS CONTRACTOR HANDLED LOAD CLEAN UP AND OVERPACKING.  SEVEN OF TWENTY-FOUR 5 GALLON PAILS WERE LEAKING ACCOUNT CONTACTING A CRATE AFTER SLIDING OFF A PALLET CONTAINING THREE TIERS LOOSELY STRETCH WRAPPED TOGETHER.  THREE ADDITIONAL PAILS WERE DAMAGED BUT DID NOT LEAK.  THE LOAD WAS RELEASED FOR DRAYAGE TO A LOCAL DESTINATION.

column168: CAR INSPECTORS REPORTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM UNDERSIDE OF CAR.  THIS WAS A RESIDUE SHIPMENT OF SULFURIC ACID, 8, UN1830 THAT WAS MOVING TO A TANK CAR REPAIR/MAINTENANCE FACILITY.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE THE BOTTOM WASHOUT FITTINGS.  THE TANK CAR OWNER WAS CONTACTED TO HANDLE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  A RETAINING POOL WAS PLACED UNDER THE DEFECTIVE FITTING AFTER THE CAR WAS PLACED ON AN ISOLATION TRACK. EVIDENCE(EXTERNAL CAULKING) OF A PREVIOUS PROBLEM WAS NOTED.  ULTIMATELY A CONTRACTOR REPRESENTING THE CAR LEESEE REPAIRED THE INNER GASKET OF THE BOTTOM WASHOUT.  PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED AND TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE COUPLING A TRACK IN THE DEPARTURE YARD, A SWITCHMAN WAS SPLASHED ON THE HEAD AND FACE BY PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF THIS CAR. THE EMPLOYEE, ASSISTED BY OTHER CREW MEMBERS, IMMEDIATELY WASHED THE CONTACTED AREA WITH WATER(PER THE INSTRUCTIONS IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION).  THE EMPLOYEE WAS THEN TAKEN FOR A MEDICAL EXAM.  THE DOCTOR RELEASED THE EMPLOYEE FOR FULL DUTY, BUT CAUTIONED TO AVOID EXPOSURE TO EXTREME HOT AND COLD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND 3 OF 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS IN PLACE, 3 LOOSE(BUT IN PLACE) AND 2 DISCONNECTED AND HANGING.  ALL BOLTS WERE PROPERLY POSITIONED AND SECURED.  RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS REMOVED/NEUTRALIZED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THIS CONTAINER WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN A STORAGE LOT AWAITING PICK UP BY A DRAYMAN.  IT HAD CONCLUDED THE RAIL TRANSPORTATION OF ITS CYCLE.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED LOAD AFTER ISOLATING IT.  THE SHIPPERS'S CONTRACTOR HANDLED REMEDIATION OF THE LOAD.  A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE CONTACTED A RAISED SCREW IN THE FLOOR.  THIS APPARENTLY OCCURRED DURING LOADING.  THE RESULTING HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/4" IN DIAMETER IN THE BOTTOM CHIME.  OVERALL LOAD WAS IN GOOD CONDITION WITH TYGARD/TYPATCH IN PLACE AND SEPARATION BOARDS BETWEEN LAYERS.

WHILE THIS TANK CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED AT BELEN YARD, A RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS INHALED BY A SWITCHMAN BESIDE THE CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE CAR TO HAVE A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISK AND REPLACED SAME.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED FOR CLEANING AND NEUTRALIZATION OF THE ESTIMATED 3 GALLONS RELEASED. INJURIES REPORTED BY THE SWITCHMAN INCLUDED IRRITATED EYES AND NAUSEA. MEDICAL EXAM WAS CONDUCTED.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THIS TANK CAR WAS LOCATED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, EXCESSIVE INTERNAL PRESSURE CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM DISTILLATES TO BE VENTED THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT RAN DOWN THE CAR SIDES AND ON TO THE GROUND.  REMEDIATION WAS EFFECTIVELY HANDLED BY THE FACILITY'S ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, UNDER SUPERVISION OF STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES. THIS WAS NOT AN OCCURRENCE DURING RAIL TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: A SWITCH CREW OBSERVED LEAKING PRODUCT ON CAR SIDES WHILE THE TANK CAR WAS WAITING TO BE SWITCHED.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND MISSING GASKETS BETWEEN TANK CAR FLANGE AND LIQUID LINE VALVE.  A TEMPORARY REPAIR WAS MADE AFTER THE CAR WAS PLACED ON AN ISOLATION TRACK.  THE SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR PERMANENT REPAIRS(WHICH WERE COMPLETED PRIOR TO RETURNING THE CAR TO ITS TRANSPORTATION CYCLE).  THIS WAS A TWO COMPARTMENT CAR, WITH A RELEASE ONLY FROM THE 'A' END FITTINGS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: THIS TANK CONTAINER WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING WHEN BEING INSPECTED AT THE OUTBOUND GATE INSPECTION(AFTER COMPLETING THE RAIL TRANSPORTATION CYCLE). BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND LIQUID PRESENT AT THE MANWAY OVERFLOW BOX DRAIN LINES.  ONE LINE HAD BEEN PLUGGED WITH A RAG.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS CHECKED AND ALL 8 BOLTS WERE SUFFICIENTLY TIGHT.  THE OUTAGE WAS THEN CHECKED AND ALSO FOUND TO BE SUFFICIENT.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT POOR LOADING METHODS RESULTED IN SPILLED PRODUCT NEAR THE MANWAY.  DUE TO THE THICK VISCOSITY OF THE LIQUID, IT WOULD HAVE BEEN SLOW TO PASS THROUGH THE DRAIN LINES WHERE IT WAS FOUND DURING THE OUTBOUND INSPECTION.
PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADE.
SPILLAGE DUE TO LOOSE CAP ON ONE OF THE CANS.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, DOCKMAN PUNCTURED CARTON WHILE REMOVING OTHER FREIGHT.  THE DAMAGED CARGO WAS RECOOPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND WITH A CRACK IN SIDE CAUSED BY A SKID THAT SHIFTED IN TRANSIT.  THE CREASE IN THE DENT WAS SEEPING.  THE SEEPAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9 AND THE CRACK WAS PATCHED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND RECOOPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
CORROSIVE MATERIAL ATE THROUGH BOTTOM OF DRUMS.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE RECOOPED AND OVERPACKED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHEN DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER, ONE CARTON WAS FOUND CRUSHED. SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9.  THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS RECOOPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: WHILE LOADING FREIGHT A CARTON WAS DROPPED, CAUSING ONE GLASS BOTTLE TO SHATTER.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED, RECOOPED AND THE DAMAGED CARTON RECOOPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A TOTE WAS FOUND SEEPING FROM RUST/CORROSION WHERE THE METAL LEGS ATTACH TO THE TANK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE TERMINAL.  THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK WERE RECOOPED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKAGING.

DOCKMAN PUNCTURED DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADES.  PH-9 WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL AND THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS RECOOPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A DRUM WAS FOUND SEEPING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE SEAL OF BUNG.  THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9 AND THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND RECHECKED FOR LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

WHILE DELIVERING FREIGHT TO THE CONSIGNEE THE DRIVER FOUND ONE PAIL THAT HAD FALLEN OVER IN TRANSIT CAUSING FLAVORING TO SEEP FROM PAIL.  THE PAIL WAS UPRIGHTED, CLEANED, AND THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE FREIGHT.  THE SPILLAGE WAS TAKEN UP WITH FLOOR DRY AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

AFTER CONSULTING MY DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, I CONTAINED SPILL IN A DMP SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DOT CAGE. THE BALANCE WAS SENT THROUGH THE UPS REPACK SYSTEM TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE WHEN A SMALL LEAK WAS DISCOVERED FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED TO CAPTURE THE SEEPAGE AND A VALVE GASKET WAS LATER REPLACED.

DRIVER CONNECTED HOSES, CUSTOMER OPERATOR WAS READY FOR THE PRODUCT, AND WHEN DRIVER OPENED INTERNAL VALVE OF TANK TRUCK THE FIRST LENGTH OF HOSE SEPARATED FROM THE SECOND LENGTH OF HOSE.  DRIVER HAD FAILED TO SECURE THESE WITH TIE-DOWNS OR TAPE TO BE SURE THE CAM-LOCK FITTINGS STAYED CLOSED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP SPILLED PRODUCT.

DURING THE UNLOAD PROCESS, A DRIP BEGAN ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK TRUCK.  IT WAS DISCOVERED AND CONTAINERS PLACED TO CATCH PRODUCT. EVALUATION SHOWED TRAILER WAS COMPROMISED IN A MAJOR WAY.  PLAN WAS ACTIVATED TO PUMP 2000 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT INTO THE PLANT WASTE CONTROL SYSTEM FOR TREATMENT.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A DIFFERENT TANK TRUCK.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR - E.M.C. OF SAN ANTONIO WAS CALLED IN TO PERFORM SITE CLEANUP.  CARRIER SENT TWO TRAINED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TECHNICIANS TO THE INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO EVACUATIONS.  TANK TRUCK WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR TESTING AND POSSIBLE REPAIRS.

BOTH OF THEM WERE WEARING PROTECTIVE CLOTHING BUT ACID GOT AROUND THEIR FACE SHIELDS AND THEY WERE BURNED ON THE FACE AND NECK AREA.  BOTH WERE GIVEN FIRST AID, THEN TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  BOTH WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.  INDSPEC CHEMICAL CO PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP AREA.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE SURFACE ON WHICH IT OCCURRED. AGREEMENT REACHED BETWEEN THE DU PONT COMPANY AND CARRIER FOR MODIFICATION OF THIS TANK TRAILER.

column168: AMERICAN TRANSPORT INC. DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY SITE, GUAGED THE TANKS FOR SAFE FILL LEVEL AND ESTABLISHED HE COULD MAKE DELIVERY WITH AN EXTRA 1250 GALLONS OF ROOM BETWEEN TWO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  THE DRIVER DELIVERED 4200 GALLONS OF NOLEAD INTO A 12,000 UST.  THE DRIVER THEN SWITCHED OVER TO A MANIFOLDED 10,000 UST AND ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER 3300 GALLONS OF NOLEAD INTO THIS TANK.  325 GALLONS FROM COMPLETION OF THE 10,000 GALLON TANK THE DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT HAD STOPPED FLOWING INTO THE TANK.  WHILE THE DRIVER WAS TRYING TO FIGURE OUT WHY THE PRODUCT STOPPED HE HEARD A "POP" AND NOTICED THAT PRODUCT WAS OVERFILLING OUT OF THE 12,000 GALLONG UST.  THE DRIVER BEGAN CONTAINMENT AND CONTROL PROCEDURES AND NOTIFIED THE LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SERVICE.  ATI'S ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND BEGAN CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PICKED-UP AND DISPOSED OF AS REQUIRED BY FEDERAL AND LOCAL LAWS.  THIS INCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT AS TO WHY THE TANK OVERFILL PROTECTION FAILED AND WHY THE TANKS OVERFILLED WITH AMPLE ROOM FOR DELIVERY.  ATI AND CITGO HAVE ESTABLISHED A SAFE FILL LIMIT NOT TO EXCEED 90% OF KNOWN TANK CAPACITY.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL TO CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH KIMBALL ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBALL, NE. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT 4930 SUPERIOR AVENUE IN LINCOLN, NE IN ORDER TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE CUSTOMER PICK-UP. THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND NOTED THAT ONE OF THE CUBIC YARD BOXES ACCEPTED FOR SHIPMENT FROM A PREVIOUS STOP HAD FAILED ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF LIQUID TO ESCAPE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND NOTIFIED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE TO INITIATE RESPONSE ACTIVIITIES. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW CLEAN-UP CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ESCORTED THE VEHICLE TO THEIR TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS MET BY A SECOND CLEAN HARBORS' VAN TRAILER. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW THEN TRANSFERRED THE INTACT CONTAINERS FROM THE INITIAL VAN TRAILER ONTO THE SECOND VAN TRAILER IN ORDER TO FACILITATE THE RESPONSE ACTIVITIES. ONCE THIS WAS COMPLETE, THE MATERIAL WHICH WAS RELEASED WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING PAPER. THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS THEN TRANSFERRED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS WHICH WERE ALSO TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. ** PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGED WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE NOT TO BE A SHIPPABLE CONTAINER.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE ALTERNATE CONTAINERS FOR MATERIALS THAT COULD CONTAIN LIQUIDS NOTVISIBLE AT TIME OF LOADING BUT WHICH COULD PHASE OUT

SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE HAZMAT TOTE ON A POSSIBLE SPILL AT 0005. UPON ARRIVAL TEAM FOUND ONE BOX OR CORROSIE LIQUID LEAKING. DRIVER TOOK EXTERNAL VALVE APART AND PUT STEAM HOSE UP INTO THE LINE TO THAW PRODUCT.  WHEN PRODUCT FINALLY THAWED OUT THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY TO STOP FLOW, SO THE ENTIRE LOAD WENT ONTO THE GROUND.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT AND IN THE ADJOINING SUMP AREA. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON GENERAL MOTORS PROPERTY AND CLEANED UP BY INLAND WATERS CO, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY HIRED BY BULK TRANSPORT.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT A FOREIGN OBJECT IN THE PRODUCT HELD THE INTERNAL VALVE FROM CLOSING.  PREVENTION OF FUTURE OCCURRENCES WILL BE ACHIEVED BY VACUUM TESTING ALL INTERNAL VALVES AND RETRAINING DRIVERS TO NEVER DISASSEMBLE VALVES ON FROZEN PRODUCT.

INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR HAD A BROKEN RUPTURE DISC.  RODABOUGH REPLACED THE DISC WITH A LIKE DISC.  THE DISC IS IN A SAFETY VENT MOUNTED ON THE MANWAY COVER.
WHILE DRIVER WAS PUMPING OIL, HOSE SPRUNG HOLE. TRUCK WAS BROUGHT BACK TO SHOP AND HOSE WAS REPLACED
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: SEALED REFRIGERATED SHIPPING CONTAINER AND CHASSIS WERE BEING TRANSPORTED FROM INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA TO ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY.  AS A DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON I-80 NEAR GERARD, OHIO, HE WAS ADVISED BY CB RADIO FROM ANOTHER DRIVER THAT HE MIGHT HAVE SOMETHING LEAKING FROM THE CONTAINER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE INTERSTATE AND PULLED TO A REMOTE CORNER OF THE PETRO TRUCK STOP PARKING LOT.  UPON INSPECTION, A SMALL LEAK FROM THE CONTAINER WAS FOUND.  THE TRUMBLE COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO HIS LOCATION AND UPON ARRIVAL, LOCATED TWO LEAKING DRUMS, OVERPACKED THEM AND CLEANED UP ALL SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE LOAD WAS RE-SECURED WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO REILLY INDUSTRIES IN INDIANAPOLIS.

IC CARMAN WAS DOING DAILY YARD INSPECTIONS AT OUR GEISMAR YARD WHEN HE SPOTTED TANK CAR RPBX17310 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CENTER OF CAR.  HE NOTIFIED YARDMASTER.  BROOK WEBER OF CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER #52315.  WEBER CALLED SHIPPER, RHONE POULENC BASIC CHEMICAL AND BILL HUBBS OF RHONE POLUENC CALLED IC FIELD PEOPLE TO NOTIFY THEM THAT ARCADIAN WOULD BE HIS EMERGENCY RESPONDER.  ARCADIAN RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND CONFIRMED THAT THE INNER LINER HAD FAILED AND THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED.  IC MOVED EMPTY TANK CAR TO AREA AND ARCADIAN TEAM DID TRANSFER AND ALL CLEAN-UP OF AREA.
TANK WAS STUCK.  CUSTOMER MAY BE BUYING ELSEWHERE.  WE HAVE TO CHECK OUT.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column168: USED DECISION TREE.  FOLLOWED RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  DONNED PPE, USED PROPER ABSORBENT.  DMP WASTE.

RESPONDED TO THE PURPLE BELT TO A LEAKING PACKAGE.  1 OF 1 PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE COMPLETE CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP CAGE FOLLOWING THE PROPER HAZMAT PROCEDURES.  AN ISP CARD WAS FILLED OUT.

ON 3/2/97 A ODOR WAS REPORTED IN OUR "C" BUILDING SORT FACILITY. THE LOCATIONS ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVER, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED, UPON ARRIVAL THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS DONNED, TO CHECK OUT THE SHIPMENT. THE AIRBILL STATEMENT OF THE SHIPMENT LISTED THE CONTENTS AS PARADZZ-THYL BENZEN. AFTER NOTING THIS, THE TECHNICIAN QUICKLY BAGGED THE SHIPMENT AND REMOVED THIS SHIPMENT TO A SECURED AREA WHERE A FURTHER INVESTIGATION COULD TAKE PLACE. AFTER SECURING AN AREA AND RESEARCHING THE PRODUCT, WE BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION. WE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT HAD PRE-PRINTED MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE STATING THIS WAS COMPUTER PAPER. THE INNER BOX WAS A SQUARE WOODEN BOX WITH NO MARKINGS. THIS BOX WAS NAILED OR STAPLED SHUT. THE CONTENTS OF THE WOODEN BOX CONTAINED (4) GLASS BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW CLOSURES, PACKED IN PLASTIC BAGS. THE BOTTLES WERE SECURED WITH PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTING OF WOOD SHAVINGS AND STRAW. THE QUANTITY OF EACH BOTTLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 16 OZS, ONE BOTTLE WAS DISCOVERED BROKEN. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THIS IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED INBOUND WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURED. APPARENTLY THE PACKAGE WAS PUNCTURED BY SOME TYPE OF PROTRUSION IN TRANSIT.  THIS PUNCTURED TWO OF THE THREE AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT CANS IN THE BOX.  THERE WERE 'NO' HAZ MAT MARKINGS, LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

AS THE TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED THE BOXES WERE FOUND TO BE SOAKED WITH WHAT SMELLED LIKE DIESEL FUEL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED BUT NO ONE WAS AVAILABLE.  WE WAITED UNTIL MONDAY, 3/10 AND AGAIN ATTEMPTED TO ASK THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE CONTENTS.  ON 3/10 WE SPOKE TO DAVE GENTRY FROM THE SHIPPER.  HE EMPHATICALLY STATED THAT THE TANKS WERE NEW AND HAD NEVER CONTAINED ANY LIQUID.  THEY THEN ADVISED THAT THE BOXES HAD A MATERIAL SPRAYED ON THEM.  AT THAT POINT I WAS UNSURE ABOUT HIS STATEMENTS AND NOTIFIED THE FAA.  I SPOKE TO JOHN NIPPER IN MKC.  SEVERAL PHONE CALLS WERE EXCHANGED.  I AGAIN CALLED DAVE GENTRY WHO TOLD ME ON 3/11 THAT THEY HAD A NEW EMPLOYEE IN SHIPPING AND THAT THESE TANKS HAD COME FROM A DIFFERENT VENDOR.  I CALLED THE ST JOSEPH FEDEX STATION AND HAD OUR GROUND SUPPORT EQUIPMENT MECHANIC OPEN THE BOXES.  IN ONE BOX HE FOUND PLASTIC PEANUTS SURROUNDING THE TANKS FOR CUSHIONING.  SOME OF THESE PEANUTS HAD MELTED AS THOUGH THEY HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH A PETROLEUM BASED MATERIAL. THERE WAS NO CAP ON THE TANK THAT THE MECHANIC OPENED.  I FURTHER ADVISED AGENT NIPPER OF OUR FINDINGS.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND RELOAD CYCLE WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED, AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL AN INNER FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS BOX CONTAINED SEVERAL PLASTIC BOTTLES OF SEA BREEZE ASTRINGENT.  THE SURFACE OF THE INNER FIBERBOARD CONTAINER WAS CLEARLY MARKED 'CONSUMER COMMODITY' ORM-D'.  THERE WERE 'NO' MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTERMOST PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND THE FAA DUTY OFFICE FOR THE AREA, JERRY JOHNSTON, WAS NOTIFIED AT 21:00 (CST). SPECIAL AGENT JOHNSTON SAID HE WOULD IN TURN NOTIFY SPECIAL AGENT RICH NOER THE FAA HAZMAT COORDINATOR FOR THE AREA WHO WOULD MAKE THE VISIT TO THE SPILL LOCATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINING A LIQUID THAT SMELLED AND APPEARED TO BE SOME TYPE OF ALCOHOL.  THERE WERE NO HAZ MAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INSPECTION BY THE FAA SPECIAL AGENT JOE BALLAS  WHO RESPONSED TO THE CALL AND EVIDENTLY FELT THAT THIS MAY BE AN ILLEGAL CONTROLLED SUBSTANCE AS WELL.  THE PHILADELPHIA STATE POLICE WAS CALLED IN AS WELL AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THAT OFFICE TOOK POSSESSION OF THE SHIPMENT WITH SPECIAL AGENT BALLAS'S CONCURRANCE.  A DETERMINATION WILL BE MADE AS TO THE EXACT NATURE OF THE SUBSTNACE BY THAT OFFICE.

A REPRESENTATIVE OF VULCAN CHEMICALS (BILL), HEARD AN UNUSUAL BLOWING COMING FROM ACFX 89144, A TANK CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION, BEING UNLOADED IN TO A WAITING GLESS BROTHERS TANK TRUCK.  IN CHECKING BILL FOUND THE UNLOADING HOSE HAD DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRUCK.  BILL PROCEEDED TO SHUT OFF THE UNLOADING VALVE OFF STOPPING THE LEAK.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON DOOR 201.  IT WAS CONTAINED & TAKEN TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL WEARING PPE AND USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS.  SPRINKLED SODIUM BICARBONATE AND FLOOR DRY, I USED DH TAPE UNTIL IT READ 7.0 (NEUTRAL).  PUT ABSORBED MATERIAL INTO PLASTIC BAG AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING A 1981 FORD BODY LOAD FUEL TRUCK TO THE WELL SITE TO REFUEL TRUCKS ON LOCATION.  CARGO TANK ON FUEL TRUCK WAS A NON-DOT SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK SUITABLE FOR TRANSPORT OF LIQUIDS.  EMPLOYEE APPLIED BRAKES ON SLIPPERY ROAD SURFACE AND TRUCK SKID OFF ROAD ONTO LEFT SIDE.  APPX 200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL LEAKED OUT BEFORE UNIT WAS SET UPRIGHT.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE DEPARTMENT (RPT # 379903). column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL IN OUTBOUND 7 BAY 937.  I USED MY DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO MY RESPONSE SHEETS FOR AN OXIDIZER.  I DONNED PROPER PPE, I PROCESSED THE DAMAGED MATERIAL THROUGH THE DMP.  BALANCE RTS THROUGH REPACK PROGRAM.  DIR# 5791083

I RESPONDED TO A LEAKING CORROSIVE IN FEEDER #290409 BAY 51 WEST PRIMARY. AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE, WHICH LED TO LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, AND DONNING THE PROPER PPE, I MEASURED THE PH OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WHICH WAS 2.  I THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE TO A PH 7, PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THRU DMP PROCEDURES, AND SENT THE BALANCE THRU THE UPS/HERITAGE REPACK PROGRAM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. DIR #6130973.

RESPONDED TO OUTBOUND 1 BULK BELT.  I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A CORROSIVE LIQUID.  I THEN PH TESTED TO A LEVEL OF 13, USING SODIUM BICARBONATE I NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID TO A PH LEVEL TEST OF 7.  I THEN PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM AND RETURNED THE BALANCE TO THE SHIPPER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT 1400HRS ON 3-4-97 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT HASTINGS, NE; LEVEL YARD.  CTS MGR LERCH NOTED VAPOR LEAKING FROM THE PLUG OF THE 2 INCH VAPOR BALL VALVE.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE VALVE HAD FAILED AND VAPOR WAS LEAKING FROM AN IMPROPERLY SECURED 2 INCH VALVE PLUG. MGR LERCH REMOVED 2 INCH PLUG, APPLIED TEFLON TAPE TO PLUG THREAD AND SECURED PLUG IN VALVE, STOPPING RELEASE.  AFTER SECURING CAR, MGR LERCH TAGGED VALVE INDICATING THAT IT LEAKY CONDITION.  AT 1550 HRS ON 3-5-97, MGR LERCH CONTACTED FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, JACK CURRY, MGR OF SAFETY AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND ADVISED.  MR. CURRY ADVISED THAT CAR WOULD BE SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS AFTER IT WAS OFF-LOADED.

UPRR MTO JERRY ADAMS REPORTED TANK CAR RCRX 1365 HAD A CLOUD OF VAPOR AROUND IT AFTER GOING OVER THE HUMP.  CAR WAS IN 19 BOWL. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD ACTIVATED, POSSIBLY TO RELIEVE HYDRAULIC SURGE PRESSURE, AND WAS NOT A LEAKING CAR.  APPROX. 1 QUART OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED WHEN THE VALVE OPENED.  THE VAPOR DISSIPATED WITH NO INJURY OR EXPOSURE INCURRED.  THE TERMINAL EMERGENCY PLAN WAS IMPLEMENTED.  THE RIP TRACK AND SUPPLY ROOM WERE EVACUATED BECAUSE OF THE CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE INITIAL VAPOR RELEASE.  THE ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN AND THE INCIDENT CONCLUDED AT 0740 HRS.

column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION WITH RON ALBER, BOE/AAR INSPECTOR, NOTED TANK CAR ADMX29394 LEAKING VAPORS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT INTERIOR VACUUM RELIEF VALVE HAD BEEN PLUGGED.  PLUG HAD LOOSENED AND ALLOWED PIPE TAPE TO DETERIORATE. TIGHTENED PLUG WHICH STOPPED LEAKING.

UPRR CAR FOREMAN MIKE SIKES REPORTED TANK CAR DUPX 19746 RESIDUE, ENTRAINED ON THE NPFW 24 EMITTED A SMALL CLOUD OF VAPOR.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE CAR LOCATION AND FOUND A BLOWN FRANGIBLE DISC, OSECO #100.  THE DISC WAS CHANGED OUT WITH LIKE KIND.  THE CAR AND TRAIN WERE RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

MR. B WATER'S OF NCV WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT, WHEN HE PUNCTURED DRUM THAT WAS BEHIND THE SKID. FAILING TO PAY ATTENTION TO HIS SURROUNDINGS WHEN DEALING WITH HAZ MAT, LOI WAS ISSUED.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR EXTENDED FORK BEYOND SKID.  HE WAS UNLOADING AND FORK BLADE PUNCTURED DRUM.  DRUM WAS TURNED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUM.  SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED FROM FLOOR AND WASTE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS INSTRUCTED ON HOW TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE RECURRENCE.

column168: REGIONAL MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY GARY WRIGHT, ARIMETCO, YEARINGTON, NV, THAT TANK CAR GATX 6818 SPOTTED FOR UNLOADING WAS FOUND TO HAVE A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE SAFETY VENT.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE BS&B 100 POUND DISK HAD FAILED. THE DISK WAS REPLACED IN KIND.  NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED.

THIS REPORT RENDERED FROM INFORMATION PROVIDED BY PERSONS ON SITE.  MGR R M STINE WAS CONTACTED BY MDI L AUSTONDORF ADVISING HE HAD RECEIVED A REPORT FROM THE ENID, OKLAHOMA FIRE DEPT THAT CAR GATX 33853 WAS LEAKING. THE CAR WAS SETTING ON THE BN INTERCHANGE TRACK 111 AND HE REQUESTED THAT I MAKE CONTACT WITH THE FIRE DEPT.  UPON CONTACT, WAS ADVISED THE INCIDENT WAS OVER AND THAT FARMLAND HAD DISPATCHED A HAZ MAT TEAM THAT HAD STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE ADDRESS AS REPORTED ON THE FIRE REPORT WAS 500 BLOCK OF EAST HACKBERRY.  CONTACT WAS THEN MADE WITH FARMLAND HAZ MAT MEMBER, MR ROBERT RHOADS, WHO HAD WORKED ON THE CAR.  HE INDICATED THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT LIQUID LEAK FROM THE "A" END GATE VALVE PACKING GLAND.  HE TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT WHICH SECURED THE LEAK.  MR RHOADS ADVISED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SET BACK TO THE PLANT FOR UNLOADING AND VALVE CHANGE OUT.

column168: MGR CTS RICHARD TUFTS WAS ADVISED BY REGIONAL MGR MIKE SEABAUGH THAT TANK CAR DUPX 26116 HAD BEEN FOUND LEAKING AT THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD BY FRA INSPECTOR KP KRIPPENDORF.  REG MGR SEABAUGH REQUESTED THAT MGR TUFTS RESPOND AND SECURE THE CAR.  MGR TUFTS CALLED CHEMTREC AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE WITH SHIPPER CONTACT. DUPONT REPRESENTATIVES H G LOWERY AND DENNIS SMITH CONTACTED MGR TUFTS AND DISCUSSED THE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE PRODUCT.  MGR TUFTS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 1930 HRS AND NOTED RESIDUE ON TOP OF THE CAR, IN THE FORM OF A WHITE SOLID.  USING APPROPRIATE PPE, MGR TUFTS DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE NO CONTINUING LEAKS AND THAT THE CAR WAS MAINTAINING PRESSURE.  MRG TUFTS DISCOVERED THAT NE MANWAY SWING BOLT WAS 1/4 TURN LOOSE. ALL OTHER BOLTS AND FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  MGR TUFTS BLED THE PRESSURE OFF THE CAR AND AGAIN CHECKED THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS, DETERMINING THAT ALL WERE TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT 2240 HRS AND SHIPPER ADVISED OF STATUS.

MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY DAVID LYONS, MTO, GREEN RIVER, THAT TANK CAR GATX 98405 WAS NOTED LEAKING AND WAS ISOLATED IN TRACK 4, ROCK SPRINGS, WYOMING.  ACCOUNT MGR LOW, ENROUTE FROM GRAND JCT, CO, HE CONTACTED LYNN RONCCO, SAFETY MGR, SF PHOSPHATES, WHO WAS CONSIGNEE, ROCK SPRINGS, ADVISING HER OF TANK CAR CONDITION.  MS. LYNN RONOCCO AND SF PHOSPHATES TEAM, NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM OPEN VALVE ON GAUGING ROD.  VALVE WAS EQUIPPED WITH A TELL TAIL OR DRILL ORIFICE PLUG. SECURED VALVE AND WIRED HANDLE OF VALVE, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  PLUG WAS NOT REPLACED WITH SOLID STEEL PLUG.  ON MARCH 17, 1997, DURING SWITCHING OF TANK CAR GATX 98405, GAUGING ROD VALVE RE-OPENED RELEASING PRODUCT.  MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION D A LOW CONTACTED MS RONCCO.  SHE RESPONDED AND SECURED THE VALVE AND REPLACED THE TELL TAIL PLUG WITH A SOLID PLUG, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  TOM FLORES, CHEMTREC, FILE #52693 WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MGR HARRY RODABOUGH WAS ADVISED BY YARD PERSONNEL THAT TANK CAR TLDX 120017 WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE YARD, HE MET WITH SOUTH SALT LAKE FIRE DEPT AND MEMBERS OF THE COUNTY HAZ MAT TEAM.  THEY HAD RECEIVED INFORMATION THE PRODUCT IN QUESTION WAS POISONOUS AND WANTED THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE CAR EVACUATED.  THEY ALSO FELT THAT IT WOULD BE NECESSARY TO WEAR SUPPLIED AIR PACKS AND PROTECTIVE CLOTHING TO CHECK THE CAR AND MAKE REPAIRS.  A TOTAL OF SIX PEOPLE, INCLUDING MGR RODABOUGH SUITED UP AND ENTERED THE AREA AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HRS.  MGR RODABOUGH CHECKED THE CAR.  HE DISCOVERED FOUR OF EIGHT SWING BOLTS LOOSE, WITH THE TWO NEXT TO THE HINGE ONLY FINGER TIGHT.  ALSO, THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING.  MR RODABOUGH APPLIED A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY USING A FOURTEEN INCH PIPE WRENCH AND A HAMMER.  INVESTIGATION INVOLVING THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE REVEALED THE PRODUCT TO BE A SLIGHT CORROSIVE WITH NO POISON HAZARDS.  THE FIRE DEPT WAS INFORMED OF THESE FINDINGS PRIOR TO SUITING UP FOR ENTRY AND REPAIR OF THE CAR BUT DECIDED TO PROCEED AS PLANNED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, BILL JENSEN, MGR OF SPECIALTY PRODUCTS WAS ADVISED.  CHEMTREC, BOB WIBLE, WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 52704.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 1130 HRS ON SUNDAY, MAR 16, MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED OF A DERAILMENT IN THE GARFIELD YARD BY OMAHA DISPATCH.  MR RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANK CAR TCDX 13123, WHICH WAS THE FURTHEREST EAST CAR DERAILED.  IT WAS LAYING ON ITS' RIGHT SIDE B-END TO THE EAST.  IT WAS LEANING AGAINST A BOX CAR AND LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN THE SAFETY VENT PIPE.  THE PIPE WAS SITUATED IN SUCH A WAY THAT IT COULD NOT BE REPAIRED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR COULD NOT BE HANDLED UNDER LOAD, NECESSITATING TRANSLOAD OF THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH KENNECOTT COPPER TO DRILL TWO HOLES IN THE SIDE OF THE CAR TO ALLOW ACCESS.  WHILE PREPARING THE CAR FOR DRILLING, THE CAR MOVED, BREAKING THE VENT CAP OFF AND ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO SPILL.  SUFFICIENT PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF TO STOP THE LEAK.  DURING THIS TIME, APPX 300 GALLONS WAS LOST.  TW COMPANY WAS CALLED TO BRING IN A VAC TRUCK AND REMEDIATE ALL STANDING PRODUCT FROM THE GROUND.  ALL TRANSFER OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED AT 2034 HRS WITH THE PRODUCT GOING INTO TANK CAR KCCX 2854.  THE STATE OF UTAH DEQ, MRS. LIZ YEOMANS, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS ABOUT THE RELEASE.  CHEMTREC, MR BOB WIBLE, ALSO ADVISED AND HE ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 52707.

column168: AT 1045 HRS ON THURSDAY THE 20TH OF MARCH, MGR H W RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR JIM OVISON, MGR CAR MAINTENANCE, THAT TANK CAR TCDX 13048 WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE ROPER YARD.  HE ADVISED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SPOTTED ON THE NUMBER ONE TRACK AWAITING REPAIR.  MGR RODABOUGH INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT IT WAS OVERLOADED AND THE FILL HOLE LOCK BAR WAS BROKEN, LEAVING THE FILL HOLE OPEN.  THIS WILL REQUIRE REPAIR AND THE CAR WILL HAVE TO HAVE SOME OF THE PRODUCT REMOVED.  MGR RODABOUGH NOTIFIED KENNECOTT UTAH COOPER, SPEAKING WITH MR GREG GEARHARDT.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFFLOAD A PORTION OF THE CAR AND REPAIR THE LOCK BAR.  AT 0900 HRS ON FRIDAY THE 21ST OF MARCH, MGR RODABOUGH, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE DRIVER FROM BASIN WEST TRUCKING, PUMPED OFF 800 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID. REPRESENTATIVES FROM TRINITY TANKCAR REPAIR CHECKED THE CAR AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO OBTAIN THE NECESSARY ITEMS TO REPAIR THE CAR.  MDR RODABOUGH NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, MRS BROOKE WEABER, AND SHE ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER 13515.  KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER, MR GREG GEARHARDT WAS ALSO FURNISHED WITH DETAILS.  HE STATED CORRECTIVE ACTION WOULD BE TAKEN CONCERNING THE OVERLOADING OF THE CAR.

(A - D) AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM ON WEDNESDAY, MARCH 5, 1997, JOSE SARINANA, THE APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT, WAS DRIVING AN APRIA HEALTHCARE TRUCK WHEN HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BOX OF HIS TRUCK. HE STOPPED THE VEHICLE ON CAMINO DEL NORTE, NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF CAMINO DEL NORTE AND PLAZA DEL GADO, CLIMBED OUT, DISCOVERED FLAMES COMING FROM THE SIDE OF THE CARGO BOX AND HEARD A HISSING SOUND.  HE IMMEDIATELY RAN TO CALL FOR EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE. MULTIPLE EXPLOSIONS THEN ENSUES AS LIQUID OXYGEN LED THE FIRE.  APRIA HEALTHCARE'S VEHICLE AND ONE HOME WERE DESTROYED BY FIRE, WHILE APPROXIMATELY 24 OTHER HOMES SUFFERED VARIOUS AMOUNTS OF DAMAGE.  SPOT FIRES THROUGHOUT THE NEIGHBORHOOD WERE EXTINGUISHED BY RESIDENTS AND FIREFIGHTERS.  IN ADDITION, AT LEAST ONE AUTOMOBILE PARKED NEARBY WAS DAMAGED.  TWO PERSONS SUFFERED MINOR BURNS FOR WHICH THEY WERE NOT HOSPITALIZED.  NO OTHER INJURIES AND NO FATALITIES OCCURRED.

I PLACED THE LEAKING PARCEL INTO A SPILL TUB LINED WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT - CLEANED UP THE FLOOR OF THE VEHICLE, (AFTER I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE MATERIAL FROM 0 TO 6 ON PH TAPE), RETURNED TO LYNNFIELD FACILITY BUILDING AND DMP AREA WHERE I PROCESSED THE SPILL. column168: ON OPERATIONS DATE 03/12/97, I BEN TAYLOR WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE LEAKING SHIPMENT IN SECONDARY 4, "B" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOCATION OF THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION, I NOTICED AN OILY TYPE STAIN ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE, BUT DID NOT SEE ANY TYPE OF HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR LABELS, INCLUDING ORIENTATION ARROWS TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE MIGHT CONTAIN A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. I THEN OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH HAVING SMALL PREPRINTED ORIENTATION ARROWS, BUT WERE LAYING ON THEIR SIDES AGAINST THE ORIENTATION. AT THIS TIME I OPENED ONE OF THE INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES THAT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING DUE TO THE CLOSURE NOT BEING SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE OTHER PLASTIC INNER RECEPTACLES I FOUND THAT THE CLOSURES WERE ALSO NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. AFTER TIGHTENING THE CLOSURES ON ALL THREE INNER RECEPTACLES, I THEN TURNED MY ATTENTION TO THE OTHER FIBERBOARD BOX AND FOUND THAT NONE OF THE INNER THREE 1000ML PLASTIC RECEPTACLES HAD LEAKED. THE INNER PLASTIC RECEPTACLES HAD THE MANUFACTURES LABEL AFFIXED TO THEM THAT STATED THEY WERE "COMBUSTIBLE" AND THE PRODUCT NAME WERE NAPHTHA, HYDROTREATED HEAVY" I PUT THE SHIPMENT IN A PLASTIC BAG AND RETURNED TO OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNTIL IT IS INVESTIGATED BY A FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION SECURITY AGENT. ONCE THE SHIPMENT IS RELEASED, IT WILL BE EITHER FORWARDED OR RETURNED DEPENDING UPON THE WISHES OF THE SHIPPER AND TRANSPORTED ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS SET FORTH IN TITLE 49CFR.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS A PARCEL RECEIVED BY SOUTHWEST FROM THE POST OFFICE (AMF) AT MCI. IT WAS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT CONTAINING MERCURY WITH A FINAL DESTINATION OF DELIVERY BY AIR TO THE POST OFFICE (AMF) AT PHX. UPON UNLOADING AT PHOENIX, THE AGENT DOWN LOADING THE BIN NOTICED AN AIRMAIL PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE MERCURY. THE AIRCRAFT HAD DEPARTED PHX BEFORE A SUPERVISOR HAD BEEN NOTIFIED. THE AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO PHX AND WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE.

column168: ON 03-24-97 AT 0050 HRS. I AND THE REST OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED BY PAGER OF A TRUCK PARKED IN THE RAINBOW CASINO TRUCK PARKING LOT, LEAKING SOME TYPE OF LIQUID PRODUCT.  WHILE I WAS ENROUTE FROM MY HOME, I MADE CONTACT BY RADIO WITH FIRE CHIEF JEFF KNUDTSON.  HE STATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS AN UNKNOWN LIQUID LEAKING FROM A METAL CONTAINER PLACARDED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE.  AT THIS POINT THEY HAD BEEN UNABLE TO LOCATE THE DRIVER. UPON MY ARRIVAL AT 0130 HRS, I MET WITH CHIEF KNUDTSON. I WAS SHOWN THE TRUCK THAT WAS LEAKING.  I NOTICED THAT SOME LIQUID PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE FIRST CONTAINER, RAN DOWN THE PARKING LOT IN FRONT OF THE TRUCKERS LOUNGE AND INTO THE STREET GUTTER AND THEN DOWN THE STORM DRAIN.  THE PLACARDS ON BOTH THE CONTAINERS ON THE TRUCK SHOWED THAT THE TRUCK WAS HAULING HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE AREA AROUND THE TRUCK BOTH DOWN HILL AND DOWN WIND HAD BEEN ISOLATED WITH YELLOW BARRIER TAPE.  THE WIND WAS BLOWING OUT OF THE NORTWEST AT ABOUT 15-20 MPH.  THIS TRUCK WAS PARKED TO THE NORTHWEST OF THE TRUCKERS LOUNGE.  WHILE WE WERE EXAMINING THE SCENE, THE DRIVER WHO HAD BEEN LOCATED IN A HOTEL ROOM, WAS BROUGHT TO OUR LOCATION BY CASINO SECURITY. I ASKED HIM FOR THE MANIFEST AND SHIPPING PAPERS, BUT DIDN'T UNDERSTAND WHY WE WERE THERE.  HIS STATEMENT TO US WAS THAT THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING WATER.  HE SAID THAT IT HAD BEEN IN THEIR YARD FOR A MONTH AND THAT IT WAS FULL OF RAIN WATER.  THE MANIFEST SHOWED THAT THE CONTAINER SHOWED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN SHIPPED OUT OF MCCLELLAN AFB, CA ON 3-18-97.   I THEN WENT TO THE OFFICE AND SET UP INCIDENT COMMAND.  THE MANIFEST WHICH I RETRIEVED FOR THE DRIVER, SHOWED THE PRODUCT TO BE "HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, NOS, (1,1,1-TRICHLORETHANE, LEAD) 9, NA3077, FC111 (EPA TOXICITY) ERG#(171)".  UPON RESEARCHING THE CHEMICAL INVOLVED SHOWS THE CHEMICAL TO BE A INHALATION HAZARD.  I THEN CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION NUMBER (206-872-7859) I REACHED A MR. KELLY PRICE FROM PHILLIP ENVIRONMENTAL, TACOMA, WASHINGTON.  HE STATED THAT PHILLIP ENVIRONMENTAL HAD BE CONTRACTED BY THE AIR FORCE TO DO SOME CLEAN UP OF THE BASE.  THE PRODUCT IN THE CONTAINER SHOWED TO BE PLASTIC SACKS CONTAINING SOLVENT CONTAMINATED PRODUCTS SUCH AS RAGS ETC.  AFTER I EXPLAINED TO MR. PRICE WHAT HAD HAPPENED HE ADVISED THAT HE WAS GOING TO MAKE CONTRACT WITH TW COMPANY IN SALT LAKE CITY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. AT 0230 HRS THE TRUCKERS LOUNGE WAS CLOSED AND THE ONLY OCCUPANT WAS NOW COMPLAINING OF HEADACHE AND DIFFICULTY BREATHING.  THIS LADY WHO WAS LATER IDENTIFIED AS LINDA SMITH WAS TAKEN TO PEPPERMILL SECURITY OFFICE AND A AMBULANCE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE PEPPERMILL.  I THEN CONTACTED THE UNIVERSITY OF UTAH HOSPITAL EMERGENCY DUTY NURSE.  SHE ADVISED THAT SHE HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE AMBULANCE SERVICE AND WAS SOMEWHAT AWARE OF THE INCIDENT.  AT THE FIRE STATION WE WOULD BE ABLE TO SET UP DE-CON IF NEEDED AND ABLE TO EVALUATE PATIENTS INSTEAD OF SENDING ALL OF THEM

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANS SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ARMONDO MARQUEZ, OPERATIONS MGR, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CA, ADVISING HIS CRANE OPERATOR NOTED A CONTAINER LEAKING WHILE IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED 'FLAMMABLE' IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  CONTAINER HJCU 721829 ARRIVED LOS ANGELES ON THE DULAT-26 AT 1250 HRS, SAT, 3/1/97.  MGR COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND THE CONTAINER TO BE LEAKING A DARK LIQUID THROUGH THE FLOORING NEAR THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  SEAL (NO PREFIX) 2851-605295 WAS REMOVED TO OPEN THE REAR DOORS AND INSPECT THE LADING.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON PAILS, STACKED 3 HIGH, WITH A TOTAL OF 36 PAILS TO A PALLET, ALL STRETCH WRAPPED TO EACH OTHER, BUT NOT TO THE PALLET.  THE PALLETS WERE FLOOR LOADED WITH EXCEPTION TO THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER, WHERE THERE WERE TWO PALLETS STACKED ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LOADED PALLETS.  IT WAS NOTED UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS THAT THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING IN THE CONTAINER TO PROTECT THE LADING FROM MOVING. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZ MAT, PER THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C. ****************** AFTER INITIAL INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING CONTAINER COULD NOT BE IDENTIFIED UNTIL THE LADING WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  AS THE LEAK WAS MINIMAL, A CONTAINER WAS PLACED TO CAPTURE ANY ADDITIONAL DRIPPAGE, AND THE CONTAINER ISOLATED FOR THE EVENING, PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, MGR COOPER CONTACTED HANJIN CORP HEADQUARTERS, PARAMUS, NJ, WHO DEFERRED THE HANDLING TO THEIR LONG BEACH OFFICE.   CONTACTED MS CYNTHIA BOYENGER, INTERMODAL SUPV, HANJIN, WHO DEFERRED THE HANDLING TO THEIR CUSTOMER, MASTER FREIGHT LINES. CONTACTED MS LORI CHA, EXPORT MGR, WHO STATED MFL WAS ONLY THE FREIGHT FORWARDER, AND THAT THE HANDLING SHOULD COME FROM THEIR SHIPPER, KENDALL POLYKEN, FRANKLIN, KY. CONTACTED MR CHUCK FRAIL, KENDALL POLYKEN, AND ADVISED HIM OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING AND THE REQUIRED REMEDIAL ACTIONS TO CORRECT THE SITUATION.  AS THE LOAD WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION, MR FRAIL WAS ADVISED THE RAILROAD WOULD NOT ASSUME RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE LEAKING CONTENTS AND THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE LADING TRANSLOADED.  DURING THIS PROCESS, MGR COOPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH HANJIN TO PROVIDE AN ADDITIONAL 40 FOOT CONTAINER IN ORDER TO FACILITATE THE TRANSLOADING OPERATION. ***************  ON TUE MORNING, 3/5/97, THE LEAKING CONTAINER, ALONG WITH THE EMPTY PROVIDED BY HANJIN, HJCU 721657, WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND IN ORDER TO WORK THE LADING, AS THERE IS NO LOADING DOCK TO WORK FROM WITHIN THE INTERMODAL FACILITY.  ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES BEGAN REMOVING THE PALLETS, INSPECTING EACH FOR DAMAGE, PRIOR TO LOADING INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINER. FIVE ROWS OF PALLETS HAD

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE INTERMINAL SERVICES OPEATIONS MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING ONE OF THE RAMP DRIVERS OBSERVED A CONTAINER LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE REAR DOORS. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #6, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. ** MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND OBSERVED A DARK LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE LOWER REAR DOOR GASKET OF THE CONTAINER. UPON REMOVING SEAL FARO 173643, THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING, WHICH CONSISTED OF POLY 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER. SIX EACH, 2X6 BOARDS WERE PLACED HORIZONTAL ACROSS THE LOAD, WITH 2X4' PLACED IN VERTICAL TO SUPPORT BOARDS. ONLY TWO OF THE 2X6 BOARDS REMAINED IN THE BULL SLOTS AT THE REAR DOORS, WHICH WOULD INDICATE THE LADING HAD SHIFTED CONSIDERABLY. FURTHER INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE BOTTOM FLOOR LOADED DRUMS HAD SHIFTED INTO THE BLOCKING & BRACING CAUSING SEVERE INDENTATIONS TO THE SIDE WALLS OF THE DRUMS. CLOSER INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE TOP ROW DRUM ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER HAD A NAIL FROM THE BLOCKING AND BRACING DRIVEN INTO THE SIDE WALL OF THE DRUM, WHICH CAUSED THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF PRODUCT IDENTIFIED AS UCARCIDE, A ANTIMICROBIAL USED TO REDUCE FOAMING AND BACTERIA. ** ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MITSUI TO PROVIDE AN EMPTY 20 FOOT CONTAINER TO TRANSLOAD THE CONTENTS INTO, AS THERE WAS CONCERN OVER THE PRODUCT CONTAMINATION OF THE FLOORING IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  ** ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES BEGAN TO REMOVE, INSPECT, DECON, AND RELOAD ALL OF THE DRUMS INTO THE EMPTY CONTAINER, MOLU 297176. SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT WITH THE ORIGINAL LOAD, AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH UNION CARBIDE, TORRANCE, TO RECEIVE THESE DRUMS. AS THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED, THERE WAS A ONE FOOT VOID NOTED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THE DRUMS WERE NOT PACKED IN TIGHT AT THE POINT OF ORIGIN, OR IF THERE WAS A VOID AT THE REAR OF THE LADING BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE BLOCKING, WHICH CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT DURING TRANSIT. IN EITHER CASE, HAD A PLYWOOD DIVIDER BEEN PLACED BETWEEN THE BLOCKING AND THE DRUMS, FROM THE SHIFTING, OR THE NAIL PROTRUSION THROUGH THE LUMBER. ** THE REMAINDING DRUMS WERE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, AND THE CONTAINER SECURED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

ONE ALLWASTE TRUCK COLLIDED (REAR-ENDED) WITH A SECOND ALLWASTE TRUCK AT ABOUT 2:00PM ON WEDNESDAY, MARCH 26, 1997, IN THE WESTBOUND LANE OF INTERSTATE 10 AT THE VINTON, LA EXIT.  THE TRUCK HAVING THE SPILL (THE SECOND TRUCK) WAS CARRYING A HAZARDOUS WASTE IN A ROLL-OFF WHICH WAS COVERED BY A TARP AND SECURED BY APPROPRIATE TIE DOWNS.  THE WASTE CAME OUT OF THE FRONT OF THE ROLL-OFF DURING THE ACCIDENT.  AT THE PRESENT TIME, ESTIMATED OF LOSS AND/OR PROPERTY DAMAGE, INCLUDING DECONTAMINATION COSTS, ARISING  ROM THE ACCIDENT ARE UNCERTAIN.  ALLWASTE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF TEXAS, INC. (AES/TEXAS) PARTICIPATED IN A REMEDIATION OF THE HIGHWAY AFFECTED BY THE SPILL.  THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY ACTED AS INCIDENT COMMANDERS.  AES/TEXAS COLLECTED SEVERAL SOIL SAMPLES FROM THE AREA OF THE HIGHWAY AFFECTED BY THE SPILL AND WILL BE MEETING WITH LADEQ AND TO DETERMINE LADPS WHAT FURTHER REMEDIAL ACTIVITIES MAY BE REQUIRED. BECAUSE THE REMEDIAL EFFORT IS NOT YET COMPLETE, AN ESTIMATED COST IS NOT AVAILABLE.  AS PART OF THE REMEDIATION, AES/TEXAS DECONTAMINATED APPROXIMATELY 110 PRIVATE CARS AND EIGHT TRACTOR-TRAILER TRUCKS WHICH TRAVELED THROUGH THE AREA OF THE SPILL PRIOR TO THE HIGHWAY BEING CLOSED. UTLIMATELY, AES/TEXAS INSURANCE CARRIERS ELECTED TO PURCHASE THESE VEHICLES FROM THEIR OWNERS RATHER THAT UNDERTAKE ADDITIONAL DECONTAMINATION AND REMEDIAL EFFORTS.  THE COST OF THIS UNDERTAKING WAS APPROXIMATELY $1.6 MILLION.  NO OTHER PRIVATE PROPERTY WAS INVOLVED IN THE SPILL.  THERE WAS LITTLE DAMAGE TO THE TWO AES/TEXAS TRUCKS INVOLVED IN THE SPILL FROM THE ACCIDENT ITSELF.  HOWEVER, AS NOTED ABOVE, THESE TRUCKS ARE LIKELY TO BE DECLARED A LOSS AS A RESULT OF CONTAMINATION ISSUES. THE VALUE OF THESE VEHICLES IS INCLUDED IN THE FIGURE ABOVE.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE SECURITY SUPERVISOR, ICTF INTERMODAL FACILITY, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS IN CONTAINER STORAGE SECTION YELLOW #644 WHEN THE SECURITY PATROL OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND BELOW THE LEFT CENTER PORTION OF THE FLOORING.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND FOUND LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND BELOW THE CONTAINER, WHICH WAS DRIPPING SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE OPENED FOR INSPECTION.  THE STALL WAS SECURED PENDING REMOVAL OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE GROUND.  THE RIGHT DOOR SEAL, BAYER 82595, WAS REMOVED TO INSPECT THE LADING, WHICH COULD NOT BE ACCOMPLISHED AS SHEETS OF PLYWOOD HAD BEEN PLACED ON END AND COMPLETELY COVERED THE CONTENTS. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE CSX OFFICE LOCATED AT THE ICTF WHICH PROVIDED THE SHIPPER AND PRODUCT INFORMATION.  AS THERE WAS NO NUMBER LISTED FOR THE BAYER FACILITY IN HOUSTON, CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO CONTACT A BAYER REPRESENTATIVE.  MR. ROBERT BLAKE, BAYER CORP., PITTSBURGH, RESPONDED WITH INFORMATION ON A LOCAL REPRESENTATIVE FROM BAYER. MR. DON TAGUE, BAYER, CARSON, CALIFORNIA, MADE CONTACT AND STATED HE WAS ENROUTE TO THE ICTF FACILITY.  ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN DECONING THE PARKING STALL WHERE THE CONTAINER WAS ORIGINALLY LOCATED.  UPON COMPLETING THE CLEAN UP, THE DOCK AREA WAS STAGED TO BEGIN THE REMOVAL OF THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER.  ONCE MR. TAGUE ARRIVE ON SITE, THE REMOVAL OF THE BLOCKING AND BRACING, WHICH WAS IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C, BEGAN BY CUTTING THE 2X6 CROSS MEMBERS.  WITH ALL OF THE BLOCKING AND BRACING REMOVED, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE DRUMS AT THE REAR DOORS WERE IN A ROW OF 4 ACROSS, WHICH MEANT THERE WAS A ROW 3 ACROSS SOMEWHERE IN THE CONTAINER, AS THE BILLING SHOWED A TOTAL OF 78 DRUMS BEING SHIPPED. REMOVAL OF THE DRUMS CONTINUED UNTIL LIQUID WAS OBSERVED ON THE LEFT SIDE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER, 3 ROWS FROM THE NOSE.  UPON REMOVING THE DRUM FROM THE LEFT SIDEWALL OF THE CONTAINER IN THE THIRD ROW, IT WAS NOTED THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM HAD METAL FATIGUE FROM RUBBING AGAINST THE SIDEWALL FLOOR CLEAT.  THE CLEAT IS RECESSED INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDEWALL OF THE CONTAINER, AND IN THIS INSTANCE, THE DRUM CHIME WAS AGAINST THE WELD BEAD OF THE CLEAT, WHICH WITH THE VIBRATION DURING TRANSIT, RUBBED THROUGH THE BOTTOM CHIME, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE RELOADED INTO CONTAINER SEAU 216764 THAT WAS PROVIDED BY CSX.   ONCE THE BILLING INFORMATION WAS CORRECTED ON THE DRUM COUNT,  AND TRANSFERRED TO THE NEW

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ARMONDO MARQUEZ, OPERATIONS MANAGER, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS OBSERVED LEAKING BY THE CRANE OPERATOR WHILE IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM AN INBOUND TRAIN.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE #6 AND ISOLATE PENDING INSPECTION.  ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, SENT A TEAM TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL, WHICH WAS DRIPPING FROM THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER WAS THE NEW STYLE 55 GALLON DRUMS WITH THE "W" ROLLING HOOPS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT.  TO FACILITATE THE TRANSLOADING OPERATION, THE CONTAINER HAD TO BE GROUNDED, AS THERE IS NO LOADING DOCK TO WORK FROM WITHIN THE INTERMODAL FACILITY,  THIS TOOK SOME TIME TO ACCOMPLISH DUE TO THE DROTT CRANES BEING TIED UP TO FINISH LOADING AN OUTBOUND TRAIN.  DUE TO THE WAY THE DRUMS WERE LOADED IN A DOUBLE STACK CONFIGURATION, THERE WAS NO WAY TO DETERMINE WHICH DRUM(S) WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WITHOUT REMOVING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS. MAERSK WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO PROVIDE AN EMPTY CONTAINER TO FACILITATE THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION.  DUE TO THE LATENESS OF THE DAY, THEY WERE UNABLE TO OBTAIN AN EMPTY CONTAINER FROM HARBOR A DELIVER IT TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY IN A TIMELY FASHION.  AS THE LEAK HAD CEASED FROM A CONTINUAL DRIP, THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED PENDING RECEIPT OF THE EMPTY.  ON MONDAY MORNING, MAERSK DELIVERY THE EMPTY CONTAINER, MAEU 767172, WHICH WAS PLACED NEXT TO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WHICH APPEARED TO BE IN CONFORMANCE WITH THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C, WAS REMOVE AND THE DISCHARGE OF THE DRUMS BEGAN.  A DRUM FROM THE FIRST ROW, BOTTOM TIER, AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE UPPER ROLLING HOOP.  A DRUM FROM THE SECOND ROW, BOTTOM TIER, ALSO AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE UPPER ROLLING HOOP.  THE NEXT LEAKER WAS LOCATED IN THE TOP TIER, THREE ROWS FROM THE REAR DOORS, SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER,  WHICH WAS ALSO DAMAGED AND LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP ROLLING HOOP. SEVERAL DRUMS WERE LOCATED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, BOTTOM TIER, WITH THE DRUM IN THE LEFT FRONT CORNER LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP, THE DRUM SECOND FROM THE LEFT CORNER LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM CHIME, AND THE DRUM SECOND FROM THE RIGHT SIDE ALSO LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME. ALL OF THE LEAKING DRUMS LOST LESS THAN A GALLON EACH.  NUMEROUS DRUMS HAD ROLLING HOOP DAMAGE (METAL THINNING) SO SEVERE, THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  THE 6 LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO OVERPACKS.  THE 14 SEVERELY DAMAGE DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO OVERPACKS.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO THE EMPTY CONTAINER AND SECU

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ARMONDO MARQUEZ, OPERATIONS MANAGER, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN DISCOVERED BY AN OUTSIDE DRIVER ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE CONTAINER UP FOR DELIVERY.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED BOTH FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #6 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR SENT A TEAM TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  A CLEAR VISCUS LIQUID WAS DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DOORS.  A FIELD HAZCAT TEST WAS PERFORMED, HOWEVER, THE RESULTS WERE NONDETERMINATIVE.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, DEVELOPED THE LADING WAS BEING SUPPORTED BY USED PALLETS PLACED ON END AND HELD IN PLACE WITH 2X4'S PLACED IN A "X" PATTERN ACROSS THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE NOR IS IT AN APPROVED BLOCKING AND BRACING METHOD PER THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DURING TRANSIT.  UPON REMOVING THE DUNNAGE, IT WAS NOTED THAT, PALLETS WHICH CONTAINED 100 POUND BAGS OF A SOLID SUBSTANCE, HAD BEEN PLACED DIRECTLY ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LOADED 55 GALLON DRUMS WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  THIS IS ALSO NOT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR DOUBLE STACKING FREIGHT WITH HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES.  UPON THE REMOVAL OF THE PALLETIZED BAGS, THE FIRST ROW OF DRUMS WAS REMOVED AND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS LOCATED.  A DRUM OF GLYCOL ETHER DB WAS LOCATED IN THE SECOND ROW, SECOND FROM THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP HAD SUSTAINED DAMAGE WHICH WOULD INDICATE THAT IT WAS DAMAGED PRIOR TO BEING LOADED, AS THERE WAS NO ADJACENT FREIGHT WHICH WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE TO THE DRUM.  THERE WAS A CREASE WHICH TRAVELED VERTICAL ON THE SIDEWALL OF THE DRUM THAT STARTED NEAR THE MIDDLE OF THE DRUM, THROUGH THE ROLLING HOOP, ENDING NEAR THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM. THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE IS TYPICALLY CAUSED BY ADJACENT PALLETS.  IN THAT THIS DRUMS WAS SURROUNDED BY DRUMS, IT WAS DEEMED TO BE PRIOR DAMAGE.  ROUGHLY 30 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT ESCAPED THROUGH THE ROLLING HOOP.  AS THIS COMMODITY WAS NOT A REGULATED PRODUCT, IT WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR MOVEMENT ON WITH THE REMAINING FREIGHT, PER THE SHIPPERS INSTRUCTIONS.  FURTHER INTO THE LADING, 12 ADDITIONAL DRUMS LABELED AS GLYCOL ETHER EB WERE LOCATED, ONE OF WHICH WAS WEEPING PRODUCT FROM THE UPPER CHIME.  THIS DRUM HAD A VERTICAL DENT IN THE SIDEWALL JUST BELOW THE TOP CHIME, WHICH WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE ADJACENT DRUMS.  THIS ALSO APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED PRIOR TO LOADING AT THE POINT OF ORIGIN.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE WEEPED SOME OF THE PRODUCT DURING TRANSIT, AND IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE LOST LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT.  A CHECK OF THE WAYBILL INFORMATION FAILED TO LOCATE THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT AMONGST THE LISTED COMMODITIES.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: CAP WAS LOOSE ON .25 GALLON SODIUM HYROCHLONITE SOLUTION SPILLING SMALL AMOUNT ON PACKAGE. NO CONTAMINATION OUTSIDE OF BOX OR TO ANY SURROUNDING AREA. WAS PROCESSED THRU DMP AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCESSING EQUIPMENT RECOMMENDED AFTER REFERRING TO DECISION TREE WAS UTILIZED. WILL FOLLOW UP WITH PACKAGE HANDLERS AND SORT FROM WHICH PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES FOR HAZMAT. WAS LEAKING WHEN IT ARRIVED AT BUILDING.

DRIVER HAD ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEES AND WAS PARKED ON A DOWNHILL SLOPE CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO MOVE FORWARD IN THE TANK.  A POLICE OFFICER THAT WAS PASSING BY NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED THE AFFTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, ST. LOUIS. (CONTACT - CHIEF BUEHNE, 314-353-7676) THE POLICE OFFICER NOTIFIED THE DRIVER, WHO WAS IN THE BUNK, AND HAD HIM MOVE THE VEHICLE TO LEVEL GROUND.  ONE THE VEHICLE WAS MOVED, THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS WAS CLEANED UP BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND NO INJURIES WERE INVOLVED.
